-- Anglo, Barloworld, BHP: South African Equity Market Preview
-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 2010-11-17T22:00:01Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-17/anglo-barloworld-bhp-reunert-spar-south-african-equity-market-preview.html
The following stocks may rise or
fall in South Africa. Symbols are in parentheses and prices are
from the last close.  South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All Share Index  lost 396.93,
or 1.3 percent, to 31,419.68 at the 5 p.m. close in
Johannesburg.  African Brick Centre Ltd.  (ABK SJ): The brick-maker said it
expected a loss after one-time items to be between 1.4 cents and
1.68 cents a share in the six months ended August, compared with
a loss of 0.52 cent a share a year earlier. The stock closed
unchanged at 5 cents.  Anglo American Plc  (AGL SJ): Workers at Anglo American Plc
and Xstrata Plc’s Collahuasi venture in Chile indicated for the
first time that they may make concessions to end a strike at the
world’s fourth-largest copper mine in its 12th day. Anglo
American, the diversified mining company that makes up 10
percent of South Africa’s benchmark stock index, fell 10.40
rand, or 3.1 percent, to 329 rand.  Barloworld Ltd.  (BAW SJ): The world’s biggest forklift
dealer releases full year earnings. The stock rose 40 cents, or
0.8 percent, to 50.20 rand.  BHP Billiton Plc  (BIL SJ): The world’s largest mining
company was downgraded to “hold” from “buy” at Standard &
Poor’s by equity analyst Johnson Imode. BHP dropped 6.72 rand,
or 2.5 percent, to 262.28 rand.  To contact the reporter on this story:
